4
03:58:49.910 --> 03:58:54.100
John Ellis: Okay. We had about a hundred and… about 127.

5
03:58:54.510 --> 03:58:59.300
John Ellis: So, I'd like to show you…

6
03:58:59.640 --> 03:59:08.250
John Ellis: how I did this, I'll show you this quickly, because this isn't necessarily… I didn't use skills, but I want to give you another example of an agent at work.

7
03:59:13.140 --> 03:59:15.340
John Ellis: So here you can take a look at,

8
03:59:15.500 --> 03:59:23.709
John Ellis: Up here, and I'll read this so you can get an idea. Look at, and then I gave the actual web address of, of our event.

9
03:59:24.500 --> 03:59:37.509
John Ellis: So I want to create a network opportunity by intentionally connecting people who uploaded their interests in a registration form to this directory. I want to make a case of why they should connect with 3 people. I'll send them an email with the people's names, their background, and the rationale.

10
03:59:37.630 --> 03:59:51.130
John Ellis: rationale, oh well. Of why they should network… goals for networking are collaboration on research, grant applications, teaching, or just broadening their view of applications of AI. I want to automate this entire process, including sending the emails.

11
03:59:51.780 --> 03:59:58.599
John Ellis: So, what's gonna happen here is that I'm asking the model to create, you know, a whole new…

12
03:59:58.720 --> 04:00:13.730
John Ellis: program, right? That would actually do intentional matching of people, so this is interesting. It's going to be writing software to handle the mechanicals, but then it's going to be writing software to send messages to another LLM

13
04:00:13.980 --> 04:00:15.500
John Ellis: To actually take a look at

14
04:00:15.750 --> 04:00:23.929
John Ellis: Your background, and everybody else's background, and to make matches based on these criteria.

15
04:00:24.970 --> 04:00:28.819
John Ellis: So… This goes on for a while.

16
04:00:29.820 --> 04:00:30.590
John Ellis: Nope.

17
04:00:33.080 --> 04:00:39.089
John Ellis: So it's… and I do have to iterate, so I… it worked for quite some time. I did have to iterate on it,

18
04:00:40.980 --> 04:00:45.420
John Ellis: For a couple of different reasons. Marcus, are you here right now?

19
04:00:46.140 --> 04:00:49.800
John Ellis: Okay, Marcus isn't here. Jesse Bloker, where are you?

20
04:00:50.170 --> 04:00:51.170
John Ellis: So…

21
04:00:51.340 --> 04:00:57.079
John Ellis: You notice that, and I'll go to the very end. One of the things I asked for was.

22
04:00:57.420 --> 04:01:01.430
John Ellis: Find people that are different from me.

23
04:01:02.090 --> 04:01:07.300
John Ellis: Well, there's enough homogeneity, where your broad interests

24
04:01:08.130 --> 04:01:16.009
John Ellis: made it more possible to match you as having an interest different from other people, because you have so many different interests. So you showed up on, like.

25
04:01:16.650 --> 04:01:19.909
John Ellis: 8 times as many matches as other people did.

26
04:01:20.110 --> 04:01:34.070
John Ellis: And I finally had to undo it and say, no. People cannot meet with, like, 30 other people. So I had to unwind that a little bit. But here's an interesting thing, so now it's… so it's ready to go, I haven't actually sent it yet.

27
04:01:34.180 --> 04:01:40.749
John Ellis: So what we're gonna do is we're gonna do a little experiment. I'm gonna say, hey, run this for me, and I'm gonna see if you start getting emails.

28
04:01:41.250 --> 04:01:46.480
John Ellis: And if you do, it's gonna be an email that was just generated, where we actually just did the match.

29
04:01:46.480 --> 04:02:01.649
John Ellis: So you can get an idea of who you might be able to match with tonight after, at 5.30, so we're gonna have a little bit of a break so we can reset, but the idea is, you look for people, you're gonna know their names, you're gonna know the rationale, it's even gonna make some suggestions about how you might collaborate.

30
04:02:01.770 --> 04:02:08.519
John Ellis: Now, have some really funny things here of, like, so, Hamid, where are you?

31
04:02:08.720 --> 04:02:18.480
John Ellis: So, yeah, so Hamid, you're… so, Hamid, you matched with Andre. So, it's good, it works, it matched you with your advisor. So,

32
04:02:18.790 --> 04:02:29.289
John Ellis: It's gonna do stuff like that, because I did not give enough context to say, these people actually already know each other. All right, but here we go. We're gonna… I'm gonna just say, go ahead and run this for me, and monitor.

33
04:02:30.400 --> 04:02:31.390
John Ellis: Oh.

34
04:02:32.560 --> 04:02:35.180
John Ellis: One thing that I'll mention here before we start talking about skills.

35
04:02:35.540 --> 04:02:39.610
John Ellis: See what this says? This is Compacting conversation.

36
04:02:40.820 --> 04:02:53.839
John Ellis: So remember that I said that there is a specific context length for each of the models. You can't go beyond that, because the model can't actually operate at that point. You're done. You can't send stuff back, the loop ends.

37
04:02:54.220 --> 04:03:13.619
John Ellis: So what agents do is they monitor to see when they get close to that. And when they get close to that, they take a look at the work that's been happening, and the work that's been happening recently, and any of the helper files that they've created, the task list, anything that's been going on, to create a brand new, clean.

38
04:03:14.190 --> 04:03:15.340
John Ellis: Context.

39
04:03:16.040 --> 04:03:20.579
John Ellis: So, here's a summary of what we did before. I'm gonna start anew.

40
04:03:22.680 --> 04:03:27.000
John Ellis: Different agent harnesses are better or worse at doing this.

41
04:03:27.240 --> 04:03:32.810
John Ellis: Cloud Codes agent is actually pretty good at doing this, but it takes a little while.

42
04:03:33.320 --> 04:03:41.360
John Ellis: So you'll see that it actually is going to be, taking its time to go through there. But we're going to see how good of a job it does. We're going to return to it in just a little bit.

43
04:03:41.880 --> 04:03:43.760
John Ellis: All right. So…

44
04:03:44.110 --> 04:03:51.409
John Ellis: Oops, see, here it goes. Conversation compacted, notice it started over here. It's reading the code again, so it can figure out what's going on.

45
04:03:52.680 --> 04:04:00.029
John Ellis: hey, and it's saying, yes, go ahead and echo yes. So, yes, go ahead and call the code that I wrote, that it wrote.

46
04:04:00.230 --> 04:04:04.439
John Ellis: And send the emails, and we'll see if it starts, if it begins sending.

47
04:04:06.440 --> 04:04:07.999
John Ellis: So, after lunch quiz.

48
04:04:10.350 --> 04:04:18.520
John Ellis: What do we call… That file, where we encapsulate process knowledge, specific process knowledge around a task.

49
04:04:18.640 --> 04:04:24.360
John Ellis: Or background that we then make available to the AI.

50
04:04:25.430 --> 04:04:26.489
John Ellis: It's a skill.

51
04:04:26.770 --> 04:04:28.519
John Ellis: That's right, so they're called skills.

52
04:04:29.470 --> 04:04:38.910
John Ellis: you can begin to understand why it's difficult for me to get the model to understand what I'm talking about, because I say, hey, I want you to write, I want you to use skills. It's like.

53
04:04:39.360 --> 04:04:40.640
John Ellis: I got skills.

54
04:04:40.810 --> 04:04:43.729
John Ellis: No, no, no. I mean skills as…

55
04:04:43.980 --> 04:04:47.329
John Ellis: So let's go and take a look at what we mean by skills.

56
04:04:47.450 --> 04:04:49.890
John Ellis: Very explicitly.

57
04:04:53.690 --> 04:04:54.650
John Ellis: There we go.

58
04:04:56.590 --> 04:05:03.139
John Ellis: So… Let's first take a look at What a skill actually is.

59
04:05:04.380 --> 04:05:10.610
John Ellis: So… a skill… It's actually a subdirectory.

60
04:05:11.590 --> 04:05:22.139
John Ellis: A skill is a subdirectory in a particular location that the model has access to. And in this subdirectory, first of all, the name of the subdirectory is the name of the skill.

61
04:05:23.080 --> 04:05:28.339
John Ellis: And then, within that subdirectory, it has an MD file. Remember the Markdown file?

62
04:05:28.500 --> 04:05:34.190
John Ellis: So it's a simple file, we're going to actually see what it looks like now it's formatted. This is going to be the main part here.

63
04:05:35.980 --> 04:05:41.480
John Ellis: The skill entity Has, at the very top, It's called metadata.

64
04:05:41.960 --> 04:05:43.719
John Ellis: It has the name of the skill.

65
04:05:44.020 --> 04:05:46.129
John Ellis: And a description of the skill.

66
04:05:46.950 --> 04:05:51.549
John Ellis: This is going to be the part of the skill which is always loaded. If you have 100 different skills.

67
04:05:51.660 --> 04:06:05.380
John Ellis: available to your agent, it's going to load up all of those. But remember, these are pretty short descriptions, but it's going to know all of them. It has to have those in there, because it has to automatically be able to say, oh, you're asking me to create a workbook

68
04:06:06.410 --> 04:06:10.929
John Ellis: I have a skill that tells me how to create a workbook, I need to load part of it.

69
04:06:12.310 --> 04:06:16.280
John Ellis: The skill loads… Only what's required.

70
04:06:17.350 --> 04:06:23.629
John Ellis: So when it says, oh my gosh, I need to have the skill, it would load first the skill.md.

71
04:06:23.790 --> 04:06:26.330
John Ellis: And again, let's think about what this means. That means

72
04:06:26.650 --> 04:06:28.760
John Ellis: You ask for something to be done.

73
04:06:29.270 --> 04:06:33.300
John Ellis: it knew that there was a skill that could do that, so it loaded it, so now…

74
04:06:33.450 --> 04:06:40.379
John Ellis: Your description of how to do the thing is right next to the request and the information that you needed to do the thing.

75
04:06:41.100 --> 04:06:42.980
John Ellis: That's a really nice design.

76
04:06:43.820 --> 04:06:44.740
John Ellis: Next.

77
04:06:44.970 --> 04:06:48.969
John Ellis: As it goes through, it determines whether it needs to have additional information.

78
04:06:49.100 --> 04:07:02.150
John Ellis: So I think I've mentioned to you before that when it's creating PowerPoints, when it's creating workbooks, it's actually writing Python code, which then creates those artifacts. It's not directly creating those, but it's writing Python code to create

79
04:07:02.380 --> 04:07:08.390
John Ellis: the binary compatible XLSX file, or the PowerPoint, right?

80
04:07:10.080 --> 04:07:20.160
John Ellis: Scripts are going to be another subdirectory underneath, which will have optional executable code,

81
04:07:20.570 --> 04:07:23.750
John Ellis: References, this could have documentation.

82
04:07:24.530 --> 04:07:33.430
John Ellis: And you can also have assets. These could be the fonts, the templates, this could be code stubs, things along those lines. As you can see, it's actually fairly rich.

83
04:07:34.010 --> 04:07:40.420
John Ellis: And you don't have to… it will only load up as it's needed, so it's not like you're taking up a bunch of space.

84
04:07:41.190 --> 04:07:47.980
John Ellis: What's compelling to me is that there's enough room in here for us to be… rigorous.

85
04:07:48.790 --> 04:07:56.159
John Ellis: As academics, or rigorous in terms of good designers, where we cite where everything is coming from.

86
04:07:57.540 --> 04:08:01.490
John Ellis: So this is the place where you can actually make sure that…

87
04:08:01.590 --> 04:08:04.630
John Ellis: It's clear what this is based on.

88
04:08:06.250 --> 04:08:08.610
John Ellis: Talk about the…

89
04:08:09.310 --> 04:08:17.050
John Ellis: I'm going to next talk about the design principles and sort of what this means, but questions right now about what a skill is.

90
04:08:20.500 --> 04:08:21.300
John Ellis: Yes.

91
04:08:21.780 --> 04:08:29.460
John Ellis: Or… scripts that might have burdened and inspiration that tie, where's that? Okay.

92
04:08:29.970 --> 04:08:36.679
John Ellis: So there's some information here which is not… it's all… it's all semantic, right? This is not…

93
04:08:37.660 --> 04:08:49.890
John Ellis: If you've written software before, you know that you've coded against APIs. You've actually done where it must take this particular format, and you have to be very careful about versioning, blah blah. Here, this is all semantic. Skills can be used by

94
04:08:50.380 --> 04:08:51.970
John Ellis: different models.

95
04:08:52.220 --> 04:09:07.639
John Ellis: As a matter of fact, I just recently, we just had a training, Joanne and I, and Maha, and a few other folks, had a training where we actually introduced the idea of skills to a model that doesn't even use skills.

96
04:09:07.680 --> 04:09:15.810
John Ellis: We said, alright, your model has… doesn't use skills, but you can copy and paste the text of the skill, and it'll still work.

97
04:09:18.000 --> 04:09:24.960
John Ellis: If the model uses a skill, then it will find it automatically, load it automatically with progressive disclosure.

98
04:09:25.220 --> 04:09:28.510
John Ellis: Meaning, loading up only what it needs, when it needs it.

99
04:09:30.460 --> 04:09:38.230
John Ellis: So, progressive disclosure. First, The first level is the front matter. This is going to be the title.

100
04:09:38.710 --> 04:09:41.459
John Ellis: The name of the skill, and also a description of the skill.

101
04:09:41.600 --> 04:09:49.590
John Ellis: And this is where the human comes in. You have to do a really good job of describing when and how this might be called.

102
04:09:49.880 --> 04:10:00.840
John Ellis: So, if people call this different things in their chats, you put that in there. They might refer to this as… they might refer to the task like this. You would do it when?

103
04:10:02.610 --> 04:10:04.410
John Ellis: Because the skill is only good if it's called.

104
04:10:05.310 --> 04:10:20.309
John Ellis: Next, the second level is going to be the SkillMD body, and this is going to be… this is… it's going to load up this when… when Claude thinks that it's really going to use it, it loads up all of that, and then comes all the linked files, everything that comes in, after that.

105
04:10:28.210 --> 04:10:31.850
John Ellis: Claude can load multiple skills at once.

106
04:10:32.890 --> 04:10:39.639
John Ellis: So one of the things that we don't yet have, but that we will have shortly, is a brand skill

107
04:10:39.750 --> 04:10:41.470
John Ellis: For the College of Connected Computing.

108
04:10:42.490 --> 04:10:52.909
John Ellis: Because, you know, people want to know the fonts exactly right. We may want to have sort of an open and fun and interdisciplinary kind of look for the images that we might choose to have for it.

109
04:10:53.050 --> 04:11:00.979
John Ellis: So if I make a PowerPoint, yes, the PowerPoint skill will be loaded, and the brand skill will be loaded, and they can work together.

110
04:11:02.650 --> 04:11:05.550
John Ellis: This is impossible with normal software!

111
04:11:05.820 --> 04:11:17.409
John Ellis: You don't get to just slap together, you know, one piece of software with another piece of software. But this is what software increasingly is going to look like for us. It's going to be skills.

112
04:11:18.330 --> 04:11:19.890
John Ellis: Infinitely composable.

113
04:11:21.110 --> 04:11:28.350
John Ellis: And bound to our understanding of the semantics when we create this, right?

114
04:11:29.920 --> 04:11:41.599
John Ellis: This is a very different way of thinking about software. And finally, they're going to be portable. They work identically across… well, it just says this is Anthropic, so they're saying, hey, it works identically across all of our stuff.

115
04:11:42.000 --> 04:11:46.750
John Ellis: They actually open-sourced this, and so OpenAI, so the ChatGPT, that's adopted it.

116
04:11:46.850 --> 04:11:56.039
John Ellis: Google has adopted it. They're… most of the really good… most of the good small, small language models and open source models have adopted it.

117
04:11:56.200 --> 04:12:00.299
John Ellis: So here's the interesting thing, when you put in the effort to design a skill.

118
04:12:00.820 --> 04:12:05.710
John Ellis: That can be used across all major LLMs.

119
04:12:09.260 --> 04:12:11.389
John Ellis: Had a conversation over lunch where

120
04:12:11.960 --> 04:12:16.180
John Ellis: The idea came across that, discip… there ought to be disciplinary skills.

121
04:12:16.810 --> 04:12:36.549
John Ellis: So, if you have a particular way in which is a best practice way of doing, say, a statistical analysis, or modeling, or an approach, or even, you know, formatting a paper correctly, it ought to be a skill, and this ought to be a skill which is provided to you by some sort of organization. If you want to have

122
04:12:36.690 --> 04:12:43.580
John Ellis: A common way where you're kind of sure that you're making something which is… which is repeatable and good, open science.

123
04:12:43.900 --> 04:12:47.389
John Ellis: Increasingly, that's going to be in the form of a skill.

124
04:12:47.730 --> 04:12:54.700
John Ellis: Where everyone agrees, because everyone can read it and say, yeah, that's how we think about it. And that's how we would like for it to be done.

125
04:12:56.440 --> 04:12:59.310
John Ellis: Increasingly, this is what I'm telling organizations as well.

126
04:12:59.480 --> 04:13:16.599
John Ellis: around adoption of AI and adoption of AI tooling, is that skills are going to be the way both that you standardize what's being done, you have insight into how it's being done, and you also invite people into the process of designing how AI works.

127
04:13:17.000 --> 04:13:21.330
John Ellis: So, that's why I call a skill a socio-technical skill.

128
04:13:25.000 --> 04:13:25.860
John Ellis: Alright.

129
04:13:28.470 --> 04:13:30.629
John Ellis: So let's go and take a look at,

130
04:13:31.570 --> 04:13:33.859
John Ellis: How you would create a skill.

131
04:13:42.400 --> 04:13:44.530
John Ellis: You might recall that I did mention

132
04:13:44.860 --> 04:13:51.720
John Ellis: that skills that are authored solely by AI are not that great, and they don't improve models all that much.

133
04:13:53.740 --> 04:13:59.900
John Ellis: They can work somewhat, especially if you have the model doing research on something and pulling lots of external content.

134
04:14:00.160 --> 04:14:05.639
John Ellis: to be able to build a skill. But even better is when you have an expert building a skill. So this is… this is you.

135
04:14:06.610 --> 04:14:22.920
John Ellis: So, before you write anything, identify two to three use cases your skill should handle. So, for example, hey, project sprint planning. This is what I mentioned before about software development. A lot of this is around software development, but we're realizing that this goes beyond… well beyond, as you're saying, software development.

136
04:14:24.980 --> 04:14:36.570
John Ellis: Trigger. User says, help me plan this, or create sprints. And here are the steps. Just very broadly, fetch the current project, analyze the team, suggest prioritization, create tasks.

137
04:14:38.500 --> 04:14:42.029
John Ellis: This document is linked, in the material for this.

138
04:14:42.710 --> 04:14:57.800
John Ellis: But keep in mind, this is a very human process. How do you tackle this problem? What are the… how do you identify when you're going to be doing this, and how do you actually go about doing this? And are there specific tools that you need to use in order to carry out this task?

139
04:15:00.500 --> 04:15:07.630
John Ellis: Anthropic identified Three broad categories, but we're only going to talk about two of them here.

140
04:15:08.340 --> 04:15:12.510
John Ellis: One is document creation. This is one of the first things that they did.

141
04:15:12.930 --> 04:15:23.820
John Ellis: Last year in September… I don't know if you all remember this, but before September of this past year, you couldn't get models to make

142
04:15:24.140 --> 04:15:25.280
John Ellis: PowerPoints.

143
04:15:25.510 --> 04:15:26.540
John Ellis: You remember that?

144
04:15:26.730 --> 04:15:34.689
John Ellis: you'd be like, you'd get all excited, you get on Amplify, and you say, yeah, make me a PowerPoint, and it'd be like, here are the points for your PowerPoint for you to put together.

145
04:15:34.900 --> 04:15:37.469
John Ellis: And you were very disappointed.

146
04:15:37.720 --> 04:15:44.579
John Ellis: Well then, in September, Anthropic all of a sudden could create full power plants.

147
04:15:45.150 --> 04:15:47.960
John Ellis: Full doc… full doc… full Word docs.

148
04:15:48.470 --> 04:15:50.000
John Ellis: full workbooks.

149
04:15:50.210 --> 04:15:54.139
John Ellis: All of a sudden, Actually, what they did was…

150
04:15:54.420 --> 04:16:00.599
John Ellis: they developed skills. And the very first skill that they developed was, this is how you build a PowerPoint.

151
04:16:01.750 --> 04:16:07.440
John Ellis: And this is… and what they did was, you can imagine, under the scripts they had, Python code.

152
04:16:07.760 --> 04:16:24.320
John Ellis: that would… that could be modified, that would then generate the PowerPoint. And then they had other things that they began to iterate on of what it meant to create a good-looking PowerPoint. Did anybody create PowerPoints, early on with… with Cloud?

153
04:16:25.480 --> 04:16:28.679
John Ellis: Yeah, were they good, or were there problems?

154
04:16:29.340 --> 04:16:43.029
John Ellis: So for example, I wanted to use, like, Vanderbilt, like… You wanted to use the Vanderbilt color scheme, it couldn't. Yes. Did you have the problem where it had, like, text that would, like, run over, or something like… like, it's outside of the box.

155
04:16:43.890 --> 04:16:45.489
John Ellis: So then they changed the skill.

156
04:16:46.010 --> 04:16:51.930
John Ellis: They didn't retrain the model, they didn't change anything, they changed the wording and the skill, and what they said was…

157
04:16:52.950 --> 04:16:59.899
John Ellis: Before releasing the PowerPoint, Load the PowerPoint and visually inspect it.

158
04:17:02.430 --> 04:17:10.880
John Ellis: Look for the following problems. Problems with contrast, problems with text outside of bounding boxes, text that is too small.

159
04:17:12.060 --> 04:17:19.990
John Ellis: Now, it got to do this because the LLM did have these tools, and they're multimodal models, or they can call other tools to help them see.

160
04:17:20.170 --> 04:17:24.360
John Ellis: But they just had to specifically say, the best practice is, before you hand this out, look at it.

161
04:17:24.680 --> 04:17:28.790
John Ellis: So now, when you actually generate these things, it says, now visually inspect it.

162
04:17:30.440 --> 04:17:34.659
John Ellis: So think about the huge advance that is from changing the wording in the skill.

163
04:17:37.480 --> 04:17:40.789
John Ellis: So, one is documented asset creation.

164
04:17:41.080 --> 04:17:49.390
John Ellis: The other main, type, application, is… Workflow automation.

165
04:17:49.860 --> 04:17:56.470
John Ellis: I think both of these are incredibly important for us, but also workflow automation, especially around research and process.

166
04:17:56.590 --> 04:17:59.559
John Ellis: We're always concerned about, about

167
04:17:59.860 --> 04:18:10.140
John Ellis: about documenting and best practice and being able to follow what's being done and how it's being done. Skills are going to be a powerful way for us to do this.

168
04:18:10.770 --> 04:18:12.569
John Ellis: How many of you, well.

169
04:18:12.750 --> 04:18:27.830
John Ellis: How many of you have labs, and you've been thinking, I really need to write down some of this stuff, so when we bring new people in, that they'll follow the process? Yeah. Okay, yeah, hands up high, if you… let's seriously just write it. Okay, keep your hand up if you've actually done it.

170
04:18:28.900 --> 04:18:29.600
John Ellis: action.

